value.value: A cell projection originating from a renal glomerular podocyte and extending to the renal glomerular podocyte foot.

A cation ion channel with a preference for K+ over Na+ ions, which is activated by membrane hyperpolarization, and consists of a tetramer of HCN family members. Some members of this family (HCN1, HCN2 and HCN4) are also activated when cAMP binds to their cyclic nucleotide binding domain (CNBD). Channel complexes of this family play an important role in the control of pacemaker activity in the heart.
A process in which lipids are taken up from the contents of the intestine.
A membrane region with a lipid composition that is distinct from that of the membrane regions that surround it.
A cell projection supported by an assembly of actin filaments, and which lacks microtubules.

label.value: actin filament bundle of actin-based cell projection

value.value: A bundle of cross-linked actin filaments that is part of an actin-based cell protrusion, in which filaments are oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which stabilizes the filaments.

A bundle of hundreds of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), that is the supporting structure of a stereocilium. Filaments are oriented such that the the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion and are capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma membrane.
A parallel bundle of actin filaments that is part of filopodium. Filaments are oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex.
A cell part consisting of multiple, closely packed actin-based cell projections.

label.value: nuclear migration by microtubule mediated pushing forces

value.value: The directed movement of the nucleus by pushing forces exerted by polymerization of backward-extending microtubules.

label.value: symbiont-mediated stabilization of host tight cell-cell junction

value.value: The process in which a symbiont organism that stabilizes the its host tight cell-cell junctions, making them less dynamic. The tight junction is a cell-cell junction that seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other, and plays a role in the inflammatory response of the host.

label.value: symbiont-mediated perturbation of host tight cell-cell junction

value.value: The process in which an organism effects a change that impairs the structure or temporarily subverts the tight cell-cell junctions between cells of the host. Tight cell-cell junctions, a cell-cell junction that seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other.

label.value: multivesicular body fusion to apical plasma membrane

value.value: The fusion of the membrane of a multivesicular body with the apical plasma membrane, resulting in release of exosomes from the cell.
The increase in size or mass of an intramembranous bone that contributes to the shaping of the bone.
The increase in size or mass of a bone that contributes to the shaping of that bone.
Any process carried out at the cellular level that reduces or removes the toxicity superoxide radicals or hydrogen peroxide.

The propagation of an action potential along the plane of an excitable membrane. Action potentials typically propagate once triggered because the depolarization of adjacent membrane regions due to an action potential crosses the firing threshold.
The actin cytoskeleton that is part of a postsynapse.

label.value: G protein-coupled neurotransmitter receptor activity involved in regulation of postsynaptic cytosolic calcium ion concentration

value.value: A G protein-coupled neurotransmitter receptor activity occurring in the postsynaptic membrane, that is involved in regulating the cytosolic concentration of calcium ions in the postsynapse.
Propagation of an action potential in a neuron, from its site of initiation (typically the axon hillock) towards the soma.
A series of sequential, propagated action potentials occurring in a single cell.
A microvesicle of the epididymal fluid, from which spermatozoa acquire membrane proteins.

label.value: vesicle-mediated transport to the plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of substances to the plasma membrane in transport vesicles that fuse with the plasma membrane by exocytosis.

label.value: neurotransmitter receptor transport to plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of neurotransmitter receptor to the plasma membrane in transport vesicles.
Any protein complex that is capable of functioning as a neurotransmitter receptor.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a postsynaptic specialization.
A process which maintains the organization and the arrangement of proteins in the presynaptic specialization.

label.value: exocytic insertion of neurotransmitter receptor to plasma membrane

value.value: The exocytic fusion of neurotransmitter receptor-containing vesicles with plasma membrane, resulting in the integration of neurotransmitter receptors into the plasma membrane. This process includes tethering and docking steps that prepare vesicles for fusion.

label.value: structural constituent of presynaptic active zone

value.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a presynaptic active zone.
A cellular process that results in the controlled breakdown of synapse. After it starts the process is continuous until the synapse has disappeared.
A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the internalization of a neurotransmitter receptor from the postsynaptic membrane endocytic zone into an endocytic vesicle.
Any process that modifies the structure of a postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton.

definition.value: This class does not cover assembly or disassembly of synapses, only the modification/remodelling of existing ones.

value.value: Any process that modifies the structure of a dendritic spine.

definition.value: This class does not cover assembly or disassembly of dendritic spines, only the modification/remodelling of existing ones.

label.value: neurotransmitter receptor transport, endosome to postsynaptic membrane

value.value: The directed movement of neurotransmitter receptor from the postsynaptic endosome to the postsynaptic membrane in transport vesicles.
The component of the presynaptic membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.
The component of the postsynaptic membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: extrinsic component of presynaptic active zone membrane

value.value: The component of the presynaptic active zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: extrinsic component of postsynaptic specialization membrane

value.value: The component of the postsynaptic specialization membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: extrinsic component of postsynaptic endocytic zone

value.value: The component of the postsynaptic endocytic zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

label.value: extrinsic component of presynaptic endocytic zone membrane

value.value: The component of the presynaptic endocytic zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a postsynaptic early endosome.
The lipid bilayer surrounding the spine apparatus.
The volume enclosed by the dense core granule membrane.
The volume enclosed by the spine apparatus membrane.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

definition.value: The ion channels through which current flows during an action potential should be annotated to the process 'action potential'. Gene products involved in modulating the characteristics of an action potential via changing the expression levels or the activity of these channels (e.g. modulating their kinetics or voltage sensitivity) should be annotated to this regulation term.

label.value: regulation of cardiac muscle cell action potential

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a cardiac muscle cell. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

label.value: regulation of membrane depolarization during action potential

value.value: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of membrane depolarization during an action potential. Membrane depolarization is the process in which membrane potential changes in the depolarizing direction from the resting potential.

label.value: regulation of membrane repolarization during action potential

value.value: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of membrane repolarization during an action potential. Membrane repolarization is the process in which membrane potential changes in the repolarizing direction, towards the resting potential.

label.value: regulation of AV node cell action potential

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in an atrioventricular node myocyte. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.
